ABSTRACT

We combined COVID-19 and World population datasets, focusing on the year 2020. We hypothesized that there would be a strong positive correlation between the population size and number of COVID-19 cases across the countries. However our findings directly contradicts our hypothesis, rather we found that low population density had higher COVID-19 cases. Furthermore, there were some countries that deviated from this trend, indicating outside factors - such as government response, healthcare infrastructure, and cultural practices - that have significantly contributed to the spread of COVID-19.

INTRODUCTION

The COVID-19 pandemic affected the entirety of the world without discrimination. It is transmitted through human contact and escalated in mid-January of 2020. Many aspects of our lives were altered, such as social distancing, working/schooling from home, heightened cleanliness, and business closures. Additionally, as the pandemic progressed, numerous side effects from the virus, such as pneumonia, were discovered. However, there was no clear understanding of the causes or which existing vaccines were effective.

COVID is an interesting yet complicated topic, and our team set out to delve deeper and understand how COVID impacts each country by analyzing their confirmed rate, death rate, and recovery rate. We believe that countries with larger populations, like India, China, or the US, would have a much higher confirmed rate compared to smaller populations like Haiti. Although this was an assumption we had, we wanted to look into data supported by Kaggle to see if this was true. Many leaders across the world had contradicting views and various policies on how to contain their confirmed rates. Collectively, we wanted to investigate this further. We believe this information can be valuable to the public, global healthcare policy makers/healthcare workers, and organizations such as CDC/WHO to better understand how COVID has impacted the world—a very prominent topic that still affects us today, four years later.

Despite the fact that we all come from diverse backgrounds and have different lives, we found ourselves connected by our shared experience of the pandemic. Jackie lived in Jakarta, Indonesia, the nation’s capital in Southeast Asia. Jakarta is a heavily populated city with a population of 271,857,970 (2020). On the contrary, Simran lived in a small suburban town in the Bay Area, whereas Eden, Nolawi, and Tilly live in the heart of the pacific northwest, Seattle. During the pandemic, social distancing differed for each of us, as for vaccine mandates, health guidelines, etc. It sparked our initial interest to interpret and compare COVID rates and population in our final project for INFO 201.

HERE ARE OUR RESEARCH QUESTIONS:

How does a country’s population impact COVID-19 trends (active cases)?

What is the correlation between active cases and deaths per region?

How does variation in population density (low to high) play a role in COVID-19 policies?

What is the correlation between recovery rate and deaths per region?

What is the correlation between recovery rate and population density?

DATASETS

DATASET BACKGROUND

We chose the World Population dataset and COVID-19 dataset because they are able to answer our research questions. The COVID-19 dataset provides a daily report on the pandemic’s progression globally, which allows us to analyze trends in confirmed cases, deaths, recoveries, and active cases across different countries. The World Population dataset is pivotal for understanding how population size and density could influence these trends, allowing us to correlate and draw conclusions about the effects of population density on the spread of COVID-19 globally.

Both the COVID-19 and World Population datasets are easily accessible on the website Kaggle and are within the public domain. The actual dataset for World Population originated from the US Census Bureau, the Federal Statistical System, that is responsible for compiling and producing data about the US population and economy. While the COVID-19 dataset originated from the Johns Hopkins University whose Center for Systems Science and Engineering (CSSE) collected and compiled the COVID-19 data from multiple national and international health organizations. Both sets of data are from highly credible research based agencies.

DATASET 1: COVID-19 DATASET

The COVID-19 dataset includes variables such as country/region, the number of confirmed cases, deaths, recoveries, active cases, new cases, new deaths, new recoveries, deaths per 100 cases, and recoveries per 100 cases. This data provides insights into COVID-19 trends across different countries in 2020, allowing us to understand how death and recovery rates evolved over time and the correlation between active cases and deaths by region. Here is the link to the dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/imdevskp/corona-virus-report

METHODS: MERGED BOTH DATASETS

Both datasets were cleaned by removing rows with non-numerical values. We also manually reviewed all the countries in both datasets to ensure that country names were not abbreviated. For example, the United States was abbreviated as “US” in the World Population dataset. After cleaning, we merged the World Population dataset with the COVID-19 dataset, removing any countries not present in the COVID-19 dataset along with their corresponding rows. Once the datasets were merged we were left with 13 columns and 172 rows, where each row represents the statistics for each country. However, in the COVID-19 dataset there were 5 non-plausible values that were labeled as “inf” and many of the values in the COVID-19 dataset were zero. These inconsistencies in the data pose quality issues, and raise questions about how well these countries documented their COVID-19 cases. We wanted to focus our analysis on the peak of the COVID-19 pandemic, particularly during 2020, when the world was in lockdown. This period offers significant insights into the global impacts of the pandemic.

# Adding Categorical Variable
finaldataset <- finaldataset %>%
  mutate(Density_Category = case_when(
    Density..per.km.. < 100 ~ "Low",
    Density..per.km.. >= 100 & Density..per.km.. < 500 ~ "Medium",
    Density..per.km.. >= 500 ~ "High"
  ))
finaldataset$Density_Category <- cut(finaldataset$Density..per.km..,
                                     breaks = c(-Inf, 100, 500, Inf),
                                     labels = c("Low", "Medium", "High"))

Between the two datasets, Country.Region was our primary key as it is common in both datasets. Once we merged the datasets together, the variables we kept from dataset 1 (COVID-19 dataset) were Confirmed, Death, Recovered, Active, New.Cases, New.Deaths, New.Recovered, Deaths…100 Cases, Recovered.1000 Cases, and Deaths…100.Recovered. This was combined with the X2020.Population and Density…per.km variables in dataset 2. We kept these variables because we wanted to specifically focus on COVID-19 trends in 2020 and how population density played a role in this. We processed data by ensuring that data is consistent and accurate while keeping an eye out for missing information. We selected sample by focusing on density and population from the world population dataset and correlating this with various COVID-19 factors. Like mentioned in the dataset section, we removed non-numeric values, and made sure country names were listed the same in both datasets (primary key). We didn’t use any complex methods though we made sure to show our data visually through scattergraphs, histograms, and tables to answer our research questions.

SUMMARIZATION TABLE

summary_table <- finaldataset %>%
  summarize(
    Total_Confirmed = sum(Confirmed, na.rm = TRUE),
    Total_Deaths = sum(Deaths, na.rm = TRUE),
    Total_Recovered = sum(Recovered, na.rm = TRUE),
    Total_Active = sum(Active, na.rm = TRUE),
    Avg_Deaths_per_100_Cases = mean(Deaths...100.Cases, na.rm = TRUE),
    Avg_Recovered_per_100_Cases = mean(Recovered...100.Cases, na.rm = TRUE),
    Avg_Deaths_per_100_Recovered = mean(Deaths...100.Recovered, na.rm = TRUE),
    Avg_Population_Density = mean(Density..per.km.., na.rm = TRUE)
  )

RESULTS

1. How does a country’s population impact COVID-19 trends?

summary_table <- filtered_data %>%
   select(Country.Region, Confirmed, Deaths, Recovered, Active, Density..per.km..)
summary_table

Even through the US has low population density they had the highest confirmed COVID-19 cases in comparison to India and Bangladesh whose population density is significantly higher. This illustrates that density may not be a large factor in predicting active cases. Outside influences like government policies and health infrastructure may have affected the active cases in countries like the US where mask mandates weren’t enforced.

2. What is the correlation between active cases and deaths per region?

correlation <- cor(finaldataset$Density..per.km.., finaldataset$Recovered...100.Cases, use = "complete.obs")
ggplot(finaldataset, aes(x = Active, y = Deaths, color = Density_Category)) +
  geom_point(size = 3) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "black") +
  labs(
    title = "Comparison of COVID-19 Active Cases vs. Deaths by Country",
    x = "Active Cases",
    y = "Deaths",
    color = "Population Density"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

annotate("text", x = max(finaldataset$Active) * 0.9, y = max(finaldataset$Deaths) * 0.9, label = paste("r =", round(correlation, 2)), size = 5, color = "black")
## mapping: x = ~x, y = ~y 
## geom_text: na.rm = FALSE
## stat_identity: na.rm = FALSE
## position_identity

Low population density countries tended to have a higher amount of deaths vs active cases in comparison to other countries. While fewer high population density countries tended to have very low active cases vs deaths implying there may have been better preventive measures against the spread of COVID-19 in places like India whose strict mandates may have prevented the infection and therefore limiting the deaths.

3. How does variation in population density (low to high) play a role in COVID-19 policies?

ggplot(finaldataset, aes(x = Density_Category, y = Active, fill = Density_Category)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(
    title = "Average Active COVID-19 Cases by Population Density Category",
    x = "Population Density Category",
    y = "Average Active Cases",
    fill = "Population Density Category"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

Low population density countries like the US had the highest amounts of active cases. Which may be due to the lack of COVID-19 regulations and anti vaxxers. While high population density countries like Bangladesh had the lowest amounts of active cases. Which may be due to lack of reporting from underfunded. These trends directly contradict our former hypothesis that populations with higher densities have more active cases on average.

4. What is the correlation between recovery rate and deaths per region?

Countries with higher population density show a higher recovery rate and a lower death rate. While lower or medium population densities have higher death rates and lower recovery rates. This trend suggests that government policies, including healthcare infrastructure and public health measures, may have played a role in influencing these outcomes.

5. What is the correlation between recovery rate and population density?

ggplot(finaldataset, aes(x = Density..per.km.., y = Recovered...100.Cases, color = Density_Category)) +
  geom_point(size = 3) +
  labs(
    title = "Comparison of COVID-19 Recovery Rate vs. Population Density by Country",
    x = "Population Density per km²",
    y = "Recovery Rate per 100 Cases",
    color = "Population Density"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

We originally believed that countries with a lower population density would have a higher recovery rate however that is false with this data. We can’t predict whether a given population density better impacts the recovery rate as it differs by country specifically. Low population density had a low recovery rate but also shown with a high recovery rate (this has to do with policies, health infrastructure, underreporting of COVID cases.

DISCUSSION

Initially, we predicted that countries with higher population density would have more COVID-19 cases. However, the data revealed something unexpected: lower-density areas had more cases than the densely populated regions. For example, the United States, with a relatively low density of 431.07 people per square mile, had a significantly higher number of active cases compared to Bangladesh, which has a much higher density of 1,160.03 people per square mile. We believe this discrepancy is due to differences in government policies and public adherence to safety protocols.

According to the National Library of Medicine, the U.S. had lax protocol measures, which led to widespread infection. In contrast, countries like India and Bangladesh, despite their high population densities, had a fewer active COVID-19 case rate. These governments enacted social distancing measures swiftly and strictly, helping to prevent the rapid spread of the virus. Factors such as healthcare infrastructure and government regulations significantly impacted our data. However, we can’t be so certain about these results because these countries also had limited financial resources and poor healthcare which led to underreporting of COVID-19 cases throughout the country. Additionally, people were weary about even testing/reporting their positive case to the government. In the future, we could focus specifically on policies per country to exactly understand how COVID numbers fluctuate based on governmental regulations.

SUMMARY

All in all, we were surprised by our findings and gained far more insights than we initially expected. Countries that acted quickly by implementing protective measures, even with high population density, managed to keep active cases lower. The most significant takeaway from this study is the importance of quick action in the face of a crisis.

We learned that the countries that had a higher density population had the lowest confirmed and death cases. Actions were taken immediately which helped reduce the spread of the virus. Compared to the countries that had the lower density population which had higher confirmed and death cases. We also noticed that these countries also had lower recovery rates.
